WEBVTT

00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:02.320
All right that's like 24 of the time.

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:07.760
All right welcome to my talk.

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:11.160
I'm presenting Crowdsourcing Research Synthesis on AT Pro

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.680
: Envisioning an Inclusive Future.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:17.280
And I'm Jay Patel from the University of Maryland.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:21.840
So I want to preface this by the motivation for this

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:23.270
lightning talk.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:26.370
Back in summer 2025 I was doing my first systematic review.

00:00:26.370 --> 00:00:29.640
So who's familiar with the idea of a systematic review in

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:30.960
research?

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:33.610
Okay who's familiar with the idea of any kind of review

00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:34.730
research synthesis?

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:35.640
Very good okay.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:39.240
So a systematic review is a very systematic way of sort of

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:43.550
assessing how much evidence there is out there in the broader research

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:44.200
literature.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:47.830
And that involves four key steps which is searching for relevant pre

00:00:47.830 --> 00:00:51.930
prints and papers through keyword searches and natural language searches.

00:00:51.930 --> 00:00:55.290
Screening for relevant reports so from all the papers that you

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:58.670
search for, which ones are relevant to your questions, and

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:01.240
appraising or evaluating the study quality.

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:04.640
After appraising for study quality you might drop off filter

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:06.350
out a few more articles.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:09.370
And then when you do that you'll then synthesize the

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:13.860
evidence that you have into some sort of prose which is suitable

00:01:13.860 --> 00:01:14.520
for publication.

00:01:14.520 --> 00:01:16.050
So this is what I've been working on for the past

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:16.520
year.

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:19.260
And the question that I was really trying to answer was how

00:01:19.260 --> 00:01:25.080
suitable are large language models for assessing research reports.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:27.510
So as I was doing this I noticed a few recurring problems

00:01:27.510 --> 00:01:30.180
that are not exactly novel but I really felt them in my

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:30.420
bones.

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:32.920
One is just that it's very slow to do this.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.850
It takes about one to two days to read a paper very

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:38.450
deeply and to be able to say something smart about that.

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:41.200
There are many such citations for that claim.

00:01:41.270 --> 00:01:44.700
It's also very tedious after you learn it, after you

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:46.150
go to the first dozen or so papers.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:48.350
And if you want evidence of that you can just go to

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:50.700
me because I've done this you know hundreds of times.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:53.660
This is actually a very costly procedure.

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:56.400
So if you have a trained graduate student and maybe one other

00:01:56.410 --> 00:01:59.160
person working on it, it takes quite a lot of money

00:01:59.160 --> 00:01:59.450
.

00:01:59.450 --> 00:02:02.350
And there are only a few citations for this sort of

00:02:02.420 --> 00:02:05.660
thing but estimates range between fifty and a hundred and forty one

00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:07.150
thousand dollars USD.

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:11.960
Actually in pharmacology or pharma companies it'll cost about

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:14.780
a hundred and forty one thousand per systematic review.

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:16.120
So that's quite a lot.

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:20.170
You know and sadly this is also an error prone sort of

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:20.960
thing.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:24.490
Ninety three percent of systematic reviews have at least one error

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:25.880
in the search process.

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:28.660
About fifty nine percent of the sampled ones have at least

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:33.110
one error in the extraction process extracting key details of methods and

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:33.580
analyses.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:36.660
And then when it comes to appraisal or evaluating the

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:40.090
study quality, well there are very many problems and I would

00:02:40.090 --> 00:02:42.260
call that foobar or I guess you know that acronym

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:42.260
.

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:46.620
And then there's also a number of other problems like you

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:51.940
use very often small homogeneous teams which limits the quality of your

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:52.660
systematic review.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:57.180
Ideally use very large heterogeneous teams so they could get through

00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:58.240
the work more quickly.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.270
Tackle the problem from multiple frames using different kinds of knowledge

00:03:02.270 --> 00:03:05.170
, different kinds of skills, and use different connections to make

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:07.340
sure you have a really great product at the end of it

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:07.920
.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:11.440
And even more problematically, many of these systematic reviews because

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:13.940
they take so long are dead upon arrival.

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:18.370
They're rarely updated after publication and very troublesome to maintain even

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:23.260
when you have a fancy sort of living web page.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:26.770
So what we would ideally have is you know solutions to these

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:29.240
four key problems, volume and velocity.

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.480
We would increase the speed at which we do reviews so that

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:34.230
they take weeks not years.

00:03:34.250 --> 00:03:38.400
We would improve the veracity or accuracy and I propose we

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:42.570
do that with crowdsourcing, increasing the team size and ensuring

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:47.520
that certain team members are always engaged with error detection and error

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:48.430
correction.

00:03:48.430 --> 00:03:53.590
We would hopefully increase the diversity of the different perspectives and contributors

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:54.440
on our teams.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:57.110
That would allow us to reframe things, make suggestions,

00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:01.710
make interesting connections and then also have living systematic reviews which helps

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:06.710
with providing timely data to people who might benefit from that data

00:04:06.710 --> 00:04:06.950
.

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:08.980
And we kind of do this thing already with open source software

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:09.960
development right.

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:11.740
So how do we do this?

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:14.160
Do we use some kind of shiny app with R, open

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:15.040
science repos?

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:18.400
Do we use like journal specific tools or journalware?

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:21.510
This question has been asked on Blue Sky actually quite recently by

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:24.480
this user who asked what is the best platform to host something

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:25.360
like this?

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:27.920
Meaning a living systematic review.

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:29.110
Is it shiny?

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:30.630
Is it a website?

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:34.360
Well you know one other user had this interesting idea of a

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:37.140
wiki which is a more dynamic approach where multiple researchers can

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:41.240
edit and attach new evidence and reviewers and then various other people

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:44.060
can make approvals, rejections and modifications.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.480
So something like Wikipedia but with additional guardrails.

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:50.780
The nice thing is that the ATProto system is kind

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:53.940
of like a full-ish stack right now.

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:57.280
We have all the sort of necessary tooling to do an MVP

00:04:57.280 --> 00:04:57.410
.

00:04:57.430 --> 00:04:59.990
So suppose you have a bunch of research posters, a bunch

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:02.480
of preprints, a bunch of fully polished papers.

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:06.000
And then you sort of discourse graph them with their questions,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:06.800
claims and evidence.

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:12.960
And push those data into symbol collections and margin annotations.

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:16.600
Then you could probably layer that on to some kind of UI

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:22.160
where users can validate the different extracted discourse graph nodes.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:26.720
Agree and then publish that into a leaflet blog post

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:33.190
which recently has been working on creating sort of living documents,

00:05:33.190 --> 00:05:34.740
living posts.

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:37.440
So if we do this, you know, I think the

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.300
near-term goal could be to leverage the existing apps,

00:05:40.300 --> 00:05:41.050
create the MVP.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:44.030
Hopefully that could be done within a few weeks to months.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:45.850
In the medium term, I think it'd be cool to

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:49.560
query data across multiple crowdsource reviews and scaffold also what's

00:05:49.630 --> 00:05:54.800
called primary research which would be not reviews but primary experiments,

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:56.360
surveys, surveys, interviews.

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.160
And in the very long term, it'd be very nice

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:02.760
if we could build interesting visual dashboards and data stories that

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:06.810
would appeal more to the public, more for public engagement rather

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:10.360
than just creating, you know, typical research reports for scientists

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:10.480
.

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.550
So a fair number of things that we can do and I

00:06:13.550 --> 00:06:16.070
'd like you to kind of get your help with this.

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:17.600
So if you're a builder, can you help me build

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:18.510
the missing pieces?

00:06:18.510 --> 00:06:20.240
If you're a scholar or someone else, you know,

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.670
can you help me test drive the MVP, spread the word

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:22.830
?

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:24.780
And I don't know who else is out here except a

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:28.860
builder or a scholar or advocate but anyone else, you know

00:06:28.860 --> 00:06:31.730
, you can also help test drive the MVP, spread the

00:06:31.990 --> 00:06:32.880
word, get involved.

00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:35.920
I would really kind of love your advice here.

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:40.050
I'd like to thank my research mentor Joel Chan for conceptual

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:43.480
guidance here and then Ronan for also motivating this talk and

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:44.400
bringing me out here.

00:06:44.420 --> 00:06:47.520
And finally, I'm available on ORCID and Blue

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:48.080
Sky.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:48.480
Thank you.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:06:57.980
Thank you, Jay.

00:06:58.050 --> 00:07:00.300
Questions, anyone?

00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:08.480
Maybe I'll ask a question about the, yeah,

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.660
just comparison, like what's your sort of mental model for

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:14.080
where app proto fits in versus like AI?

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:15.360
How do you see the two combining?

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:21.890
I'm agreeable to both approaches.

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:25.680
I haven't thought about AI as much because I think simply

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:28.690
increasing the team size would be such a great benefit to the

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:31.080
problem at hand.

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:33.710
I know that for systematic reviews, there's an incredible amount

00:07:33.710 --> 00:07:38.640
of work being done right now for screening papers, extracting bits

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.160
of questions, claims, and evidence, and also doing the

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:41.750
synthesis.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:46.220
I agree more for using it for search, screening, and

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:49.280
extracting questions, claims, and evidence.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:51.540
A little bit less so for synthesis because that's way more

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:53.120
complicated and way more fun.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:54.630
As an amateur, I've tried to sort of do that

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:55.120
myself.

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:57.280
And it's not been as successful.

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:00.000
But certainly, I think, you know, search, in

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.520
fact, I couldn't have done part of my systematic review

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:07.120
without using some AI-assisted elements into my workflow.

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:08.710
It really would not have been possible.

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:12.240
So I strongly advocate for using the right AI programs to help

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:16.330
with search and screening, although my systematic review is so small

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:18.480
that I can do the screening myself manually.

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:20.830
And then when it comes to appraisal, I have

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:23.040
a certain way of doing it that I like.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.510
And so I feel comfortable just doing that myself.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:29.190
But I'm open to anyone who might be able to sort

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:33.410
of automate custom-built checklists and things using some sort

00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:34.450
of AI agent.

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:37.440
So that is, yeah, it's quite doable.

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:38.960
Cool.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:39.460
Anyone else?

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:47.760
You mentioned using high-quality LLMs.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.760
Did you benchmark maybe like medium-level or low-quality

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:52.080
ones?

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:55.530
I did not do the, for the systematic review that I

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:58.960
was conducting, I did not do the benchmarking myself.

00:08:58.970 --> 00:09:01.550
I was merely reviewing the studies that others had done, the

00:09:01.550 --> 00:09:03.780
benchmarking experiments that others have done.

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:06.620
And so what I noted from that, which is actually helpful

00:09:06.620 --> 00:09:09.280
for this sort of meta project, is that, you know

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:12.860
, a smattering of results, the more you focus these

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:15.840
foundation models, the better they do.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:19.520
Using sort of, you know, fine-tuned data

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:22.040
, better prompts, better context engineering, those things all sorts

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:22.470
of help.

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:26.560
But I think none of these models achieve, you know,

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:28.880
expert human performance on every trial.

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.970
So it would really be beneficial to have humans and AI agents

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:36.020
work together across the systematic review process.

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:38.690
Certainly, I see them being very useful for appraisal

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:39.210
, right?

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:41.430
Let's say you have a long checklist that's useful for

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:43.200
evaluating the methods of analyses.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:46.440
You should, you should consider certain LLMs, I

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:46.960
think.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:47.760
That's perfectly fine.

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:48.560
Yeah.

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:50.580
Any more questions?

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:54.480
Maybe a quick one while Sophie sets up or we'll just

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:56.000
move to the next talk.

00:09:56.180 --> 00:09:57.480
Okay.

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:03.600
Well, let's thank Jay again.
